A tobacco association is planning to go to court to challenge the ban on cigarette sales during the lockdown. JOHANNESBURG - A tobacco association is planning to go to court to challenge the ban on cigarette sales during the lockdown. Sinenhlanhla Mnguni from the Fair Trade Independent Tobacco Association (FITA) says the association has tried to engage government about the benefits of lifting the ban. READ: Tobacco association taking government to court "We then for the next three weeks, during the period of the lockdown attempted to engage government about the advanced reasons as to why they should be sold and also the benefits of allowing the sale of cigarettes would have on the economy", said Mnguni. He says their application depends on a detailed response from government. Fita had given government until Tuesday to respond to a request to lift the embargo on cigarette sales. READ: Tobacco association taking government to court - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.